        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/Warren-Buffett.png" alt="Warren Buffett has announced his retirement after 60 iconic years at the helm of Berkshire Hathaway" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          Warren Buffett has announced his retirement after 60 iconic years at the helm of Berkshire Hathaway. Credits: Reuters
            </i></p>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Warren Buffett, one of the most iconic investors in history, has announced he <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-may-25-spotlight-h1-1-will-step-down?source=website" target="_blank">will step down</a> as CEO of Berkshire Hathaway at the end of 2025. He named Greg Abel, currently overseeing Berkshire’s non-insurance businesses, as his successor. The announcement came at the company’s annual shareholder meeting, and the board will formally review the recommendation later this year. <p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         The 94-year-old Buffett will remain Chairman and retain his significant ownership stake (roughly 14%, valued at around $164B). Under his leadership, Berkshire became a corporate empire, controlling shares in companies like Geico and BNSF. Since investing in Apple in 2016, Berkshire’s $35B stake soared to $173B by 2023.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-5-may-25-spotlight-h1-2-greg-abel?source=website" target="_blank">Greg Abel</a>, originally from Canada, joined the company through its 1999 trade of MidAmerican Energy. He later became CEO of Berkshire Hathaway Energy and helped expand it into one of the company’s biggest businesses. While respectful of Buffett’s legacy, his style may bring a subtle shift.</p>
          
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
